ce:section.ce:para:
Reactive oxygen species (ROS) are divided in two different groups, including oxygen radicals such as, superoxide (O2

                        −), hydroxyl (OH

                     ), peroxyl (RO2


                     ), hydroproxyl (HO2


                     ) and non-radical oxidizing agents such as, hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), hypochlorous acid (HOCl), and ozone (O3) [13]. The overproduction of ROS in biological systems generally led to a oxidative stress that might be implicated in some diseases such as different types of cancer [14], neurodegenerative disease [15], inflammation [16], diabetes [17], Alzhimer's disease [18], and Parkinson's disease [19]. Several methods have previously been suggested for detection of ROS in the literatures. Among them, fluorescence detection was considered as a sensitive method [20].
